{
  "doc_id": "28859",
  "text": "Importantly we found that mutations in the NAC region of ␣-synuclein cause pathology in mice similar to familial PD mutations. NAC was originally isolated as a component of ␤-amyloid from brain tissue of Alzheimer's patients [CITATION_1] , and was later identified as a fragment of ␣-synuclein [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The NAC region comprises residues 61-95 of ␣-synuclein, a region that is thought to drive fibril formation [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Indeed, all of our mutants falling into this region (G67P, V70P, A78P, T81P, A89P) consistently increased the aggregation and pathogenicity of ␣-synuclein. Introduction of proline residues into the already aggregation-prone NAC region is predicted to reduce its helical content, and may thus shift the conformational equilibrium of ␣-synuclein further toward ␤-sheet content and subsequently toward more fibril formation, resulting in increased pathology. It is interesting that the N-terminal ␣-helix of ␣-synuclein (Chandra et al., 2005) binds more tightly to lipids than the C-terminal ␣-helix (which coincides with the NAC region) [CITATION_8] , which may account for the greater aggregation propensity of the C-terminal ␣-helix containing the NAC region. Overall, our data suggest that, if familial mutations within the NAC domain were to be found in PD patients, they would cause similarly or more severe phenotypes than those reported for known familial mutations.",
